additional bundle of packages that provide it, if they need the
ability to output DVI + PostScript + PDF.  The CUPS (Common Unix
Printing System) developers faced similar dependencies, and as a
result, our CUPS installation has its own private stable version of
ghostscript.  Perhaps TeX Live should do the same.  That way, we could
be isolated (at least for a year at a time) from changes to
ghostscript.

Development of ghostscript software is quite active.  A check of my 25
or so flavors of Unix shows vendor-provided versions 8.64 (February
2009), 8.70 (July 2009), and 8.71 (March 2010), but I'm a ghostscript
tester, and we have dozens of installed versions up to the latest,
9.02rc (March 29, 2011).  One of the recent hot topics on the
ghostscript developers list has been the issue of what fonts are
shipped with the software, and there are plans to remove support for
X11 bitmap fonts in the near future: instead, they want to rasterize
fonts on-the-fly from outline definitions, so as to improve quality of
screen display at various sizes.

